                "line": "The discovery of penicillin is often attributed to a single moment of chance, but its journey from laboratory curiosity to life-saving medicine spanned more than a decade and required the efforts of several scientists. In September 1928, Alexander Fleming, a bacteriologist at St Mary's Hospital in London, returned from holiday to find that a mould had contaminated one of his petri dishes. The bacteria surrounding the mould had been destroyed, suggesting the mould produced a substance capable of killing bacteria. Fleming identified the mould as belonging to the genus Penicillium and named the antibacterial substance penicillin."
