                "line": "Despite publishing his findings in 1929, Fleming was unable to isolate penicillin in sufficient quantities or in a stable enough form for clinical use. He largely abandoned the project, and for over ten years penicillin remained an obscure laboratory observation. It was not until 1940 that Howard Florey and Ernst Boris Chain, working at the University of Oxford, developed methods to purify and mass-produce the drug. Their first clinical trial, conducted on a policeman suffering from a severe bacterial infection, demonstrated penicillin's remarkable effectiveness, although the patient ultimately died when supplies of the drug ran out before his treatment was complete."
