            {
                "line": "The demands of the Second World War accelerated penicillin production dramatically. By 1944, American pharmaceutical companies were manufacturing enough penicillin to treat all Allied forces wounded on D-Day. The drug is estimated to have saved over two hundred million lives since its introduction. Fleming, Florey, and Chain shared the 1945 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine, though Fleming's name has overshadowed his collaborators in popular memory."
            },
